Madison Avenue, east side, from 23rd to 24th Streets. In the centre is the Metropolitan Life Insurance Building, whose expansion will devour the brownstone church on the left. This is the Madison Square Presbyterian Church (1854-1906) from whose pulpit Dr. Charles Parkhurst waged unceasing war on Tammany Hall until that organization was temporarily,at least, overthrown, and its leader, Richard Croker, driven
into exile.
1894.
J. S. Johnston, from Brown Brothers.

Metropolitan Building
P.L. Sperr collection
Rec'd January 13, 1945

Madison Square, looking north across the park from the buildings on 23rd Street just east of Broadway.

On Madison Avenue, S.E. corner of 25th Street, the Madison will be demolished between 1910 and 1916 to make room for a 20 story office building. On the N.E. corner of 25th Street is the brand new marble building housing the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court, on the S.E. corner of 26th Street the former Lawrence Jerome residence, housing the Manhattan Club. With a little remodelling the buildings in this block will be unchanged in 1935. On the N.W. corner the Madison Square Garden, about ten years old, will be demolished in 1925 to make room for the New York Life building. Most of the buildings along 26th Street on the north side of the Square will give way to office buildings between 1910 and 1916; the Hotel Brunswick on the N.E. corner of Fifth Avenue and 27th Street will go down before 1910. The small new white A.S.P.C.A. building on the N.W. corner of Madison and 26th Street will still be standing in 1935. To the left, on Fifth Avenue, may be seen part of the Dewey triumphal arch. A mile to the north, seen across the flat roofs in the center background, is the new Manhattan Hotel on the N.W. corner of Madison Avenue and 42nd Street.

Winter 1899-1900

Brown Brothers, Photographers.

Madison Avenue, east side (buildings thereupon), from E. 23rd to 24th Streets as viewed across a corner of Madison Square,from Fifth Avenue. The two office buildings shown are units of the Metropolitan Insurance Co; the larger being the home office prior to tower addition. This feature was constructed on the corner site where the spired Madison Square Presbyterian Church (1854-1906) stands. The domed structure on the opposite corner (N.E. of 24th Street) is being constructed for this congregation and in 1928 will move way for additional offices for the Metropolitan Insurance Co.
December 1905.

Madison Avenue, east side, from E. 23rd (right) to 24th Streets, showing the Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. tower under construction at the S. E. corner of the latter point. Upon this site formerly stood the old (1854) Madison Square Presbyterian Church. In the deal for this property the Insurance Co. undertook the replacement of same. That appears at the lower left, opposite its former location. Subsequently (about 1928) this will be replaced by an office building. This in turn (after 1940) will be razed and the site form a corner of a block square structure.

Views 1 and 2 bear no date; No. 3 being photographed October 10, 1908. Note in the earlier photos the Taft and Sherman banner suspended over E. 23rd Street.

In the background is the East River and its Greenpoint shore.

Madison Avenue, east side, from East 23rd (right) to 24th Streets, showing the Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. tower under construction. This, completed occupation of this entire block. Eventually the block north will be similarly included.

The photographer is viewing north westward toward a background of midtown-eastside tenements and the East River. Close observation will show the J.J. Little & Ives printing plant and units of Bellevue Hospital at the latter point. At the right is 4th Avenue and the Packard Commercial School at the N.E. corner. To the left appears the new and distinctive structure recently erected by the Insurance Co. for the Madison Square Presbyterian Church. Stanford White was the architect.

text: Madison Avenue, north from 23rd Street. 1922

Madison Avenue, south from East 26th to 23rd Streets. At the right is Madison Square, the park that identified this thoroughfare. The Manhattan Club is the ornate structure to the left and adjoins the Madison Square Apartments (street canopy). On the right margin appears a portion of the Fuller (Flatron) Building. The low Hotel Bartholdi
is on the left of the latter.
May 18, 19244
Standard Photographic Service
Gift of Borough President of Manhattan

Madison Avenue, east side, from 26th to 23rd Streets along Madison Square seen from the west. On N.E. corner of 26th Street stands the New York Life Building, on the site of the second Madison Square Garden. On S.E. corner of 26th Street the Manhattan Club (old Jerome residence) has been remodeled, balconies removed. At the right is a good view of the Metropolitan tower at 24th Street. This view remains substantially the same in 1935.
1926.
Photograph by Browning Studios.

Madison Avenue, from East 23rd (right) to 26th (left) Street, (buildings thereupon) as photographed across Madison Square Park from 5th Avenue. Prominently shown is the progressive blockwide project conducted by the Metropolitan Life Insurance Company. This annex will on completion include the entire site from 24th to 25th Streets, and east to 4th Avenue. The remaining structure (N. E. corner of 24th Street), is the office building that replaced the distinguished Madison Square Presbyterian Church. Completed and occupied is the easterly half that fronts on 4th Avenue.
July 18, 1939
